---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';

const title = 'About — CodeToCall';
const description = 'How CodeToCall formats international numbers, what data is used, and known limitations.';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1 style="margin: 22px 0 6px;">About CodeToCall</h1>

  <div class="card" style="margin-top: 14px;">
    <p class="small">
      CodeToCall is a small, fast tool that helps you format international phone numbers and understand calling codes.
      It’s designed to be straightforward, reliable, and easy to use.
    </p>

    <h2>Where the data comes from</h2>
    <p class="small">
      We use a curated, versioned dataset (stored as JSON) so results are quick and consistent.
      The dataset includes:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Country name and ISO country code</li>
      <li>Country calling code</li>
      <li>Common trunk prefix (where applicable)</li>
      <li>Example formats with short notes</li>
      <li>International dialling / exit codes (IDD prefixes) used in some regions</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Limitations</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>CodeToCall is a dialing helper — not a definitive global phone-number authority.</li>
      <li>Numbering rules vary by country and can be more complex than a simple pattern.</li>
      <li>Some calling codes are shared (for example, +1 covers multiple regions), which can make destination detection ambiguous.</li>
      <li>Carrier- and number-type differences (mobile vs landline) can require special handling.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Quality checks</h2>
    <p class="small">
      We run automated checks to catch obvious issues before updates go live. Changes are versioned so results stay stable over time.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p class="small">
      For questions, corrections, or partnership requests: <a href="mailto:dusty.opsdesk@gmail.com">dusty.opsdesk@gmail.com</a><br />
      We don’t offer phone support — this is a small, static project.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
